# §1. Phenomenon Overview

## 1.1 Phenomenon 

Social media platforms use algorithms to highlight and amplify the outreach of trending topics. AI-driven bots can manipulate these trends by artificially increasing engagement on posts to have higher chances of being picked up by the algorithm. This phenomenon is called metric manipulation, it is primarily found on social media platforms. For this study, we will be focused on centralized social networking apps, specifically **Twitter (now X)**. Metric manipulation plays an important role in AI-to-Human interactions as well AI-to-AI interactions. This would be attributed to how bots can trick the algorithm into promoting topics regardless of how the topic originated from organic or inorganic means. This can ultimately lead to algorithmic amplification and spreading of non organic narratives.

X employs a sophisticated algorithm which utilizes AI to recommend relevant topics to users. It is important to note that these recommendations from the algorithm generally favours more engagement over content reliability (Corsi, 2024).

## 1.2 Problem Statement

The manipulation of social media metrics by bots presents an important threat in both the digital and real world. The primary directive of X is to ensure that users are engaged with their platform as much as possible, this is achieved by having their algorithm deliver relevant trends and topics to users. Bots in turn can take advantage of this system, this is achieved through simulating engagement with other users or bots to amplify the metrics of a given topic. This idea of metric manipulation would in turn have the ability to impact important topics on the platform such as political discourse, economics, and health information. This would be attributed to how bots can push misinformation and misleading content which can muddy the swamp in terms of content validity and narrative. (Barhate et al, 2020). This also has a long term effect on X as a platform,  as it devalues the credibility of the platform itself. X by association will be known for pushing low-credible content to users which would result in platform degradation and decline of user trust (Weng & Lin, 2022).

## 1.3 Agent Based Modeling

Agent-based modeling (ABM) is suitable for this approach because it can simulate real life interactions between users and bots. We can view the interaction between the agents and see how their behaviour impacts the system. We have created a network graph to showcase edges of agents following one another which can be used to model social media use cases. ABM allows us to create bots to coordinate amongst one another and to simulate influences on human users. We can also create an algorithm entity which helps to simulate topic spread and influence human users globally throughout the simulation. Overall, the model we came up with is a good way to showcase metric manipulation in X as we can visualize the spreading of topics and bots coordinate with each other.

# §2. Simulation Design & Implementation 

## 2.1 System Overview

For our system, we decided to model the “For You” Tab on X to showcase our phenomena of interest. Our system primarily consists of two types of agents, human agents, bot agents, as well as AI algorithm entities. Both human and bot agents are used to model types of engagement with a topic, while the AI algorithm is used to showcase mechanisms of recommending topics to users.

## 2.2 Simulation Environment

The model we found that would best represent our media ecosystem of the “For You” Tab on X would be the network-based model. We decided to go with this model due to how it both enabled us to visually showcase relationships between different agents as well as it being a good fit in terms of representing our phenomena of interest. A network based model shows clear relations between how agents operate as well as how agents can influence one another. 

## 2.3 Key Parameters

There are several user controlled parameters that can be adjusted before the start of the simulation. The parameters are broken down into two categories, parameters that impact the totality of bots, as well as the probability of agents influencing one another. Totality is broken down into the following parameters: amounts of total agents, amount of decision bots, and amount of follower bots. Probability is broken down into the following parameters: the probability of bots to human influence, probability of human to human influence, probability of main algorithm to human influence, and probability of second algorithm to human influence. These parameters value determines the chance that one agent will successfully influence another to engage with the same topic it is pushing. These parameters allow us to explore how differing amounts of agents and or situations can impact the results of the simulation. 

## 2.4 Type of Agent and Behaviors

In our model, there are six topics differentiated by color that a human or a bot agent can choose to engage with. Humans are represented by squares and bots are represented by circles.

Bot agents in our system operate in 2 types, follower bots as well as decision bots. Decision bots operate by picking topic 1 that currently exists within the media ecosystem. It will then push that topic to both human agents as well as follower bots via platform mechanisms of interacting (liking and reposting). Follower bots work by pushing topics that decision bots choose, it is important to note that follower bots can only push out topics chosen by decision bots and will not be influenced by any other factors.  

Human agents in contrast work by looking at connected agents to it and per step of the simulation can change what they are currently engaging with. Human agents have higher chances of interacting with a specific topic based on what surrounding connected agents are interacting with. It is important to note that per step of the simulation, the algorithm can also influence human agents by recommending topics to them. Meaning that human agents who are surrounded by agents that all push the same type of content, have chances to be influenced by the algorithm to engage with other topics.

Humans in our simulation also have additional behaviours such as tolerance. Tolerance in our model works by looking at how long a human agent is exposed to a topic, and has higher chances to engage with other topics as the tolerance towards a topic increases per step of the simulation. 

Bots in contrast have additional behaviours that are reactive to the state of the simulation itself. Bots will shift to inflate other topics when factors such as human agents tolerance to a topic make inflating a specific topic no longer lucrative. Bots push topic 1, then topic 2, then topic 3, and then restarts at topic 1 as tolerance builds up.

We also have an entity in our simulation that models the main algorithm for topic recommendations. This mechanism of recommendation works by looking at the total amount of engagement a topic has. Topics with the most engagement are picked up by the algorithm and are recommended globally to other human agents.We have another entity which is the second algorithm and it recommends random topics to humans periodically as the simulation progresses.

## 2.5 Simplifications

One aspect of the model we chose to simplify was the agent behaviour in regards to topic engagement. In real life, topics are constantly changing and trends emerge constantly. To keep it simple and manageable we focused on limiting interactions for agents to six pre established topics only.  

Another simplification we decided on, was how human agents and their tolerances towards a topic. Whenever a bot has chosen to go from inflating one topic to another topic, human agents would forget their tolerance of the previous topic. So, as bot agents are circling to inflate a new topic, humans would have lost tolerance to prior inflated topics. This was done, due to how humans when engaging on social media platforms will naturally gain tolerance to a topic when seeing or engaging with it for extended periods of time. This relationship also works inversely, where the more time they are engaged with other topics decreases the resistance built with the original topic in question.

## 2.6 Scheduler

For our model we used Mesa AgentSet functionality which has replaced the RandomActivation scheduler. Agents in our model are activated per step of the simulation but in random order. We chose this method because it minimizes bias in our simulation which would allow for more reflection of our phenomena between each trial. If we did not allow this function, then the agents will always activate in the same order which will make the simulation less realistic. AgentSet enables a small degree of randomness in our model, which would better reflect the nature of how agents both within our simulation and in real life act. Given that we are simulating metric manipulation, AgentSet is more accurate to use because agents influence each other in unpredictable sequences.

## 2.7 Emergence of Metric Manipulation

Metric manipulation in the simulation emerges through coordinated bot actions, human interaction, and algorithm recommendation. A topic can be artificially boosted by bots, which in turn will prompt the algorithm to recommend it to other humans. Humans then would have additional chances to interact with the topic pushed by both bots and the algorithm which would further increase engagement. This cycle of interactions in turn creates a snowball effect as this cycle of interaction feeds back into itself, mimicking a positive feedback loop.

## 2.8 Key Assumptions

Our simulation is based on several assumptions about agent behavior in regards to information spread. Bot coordination is centralized to decision bots, which means follower bots do not independently act without decision bots involved. Bots agents are not influenced by human interactions. However, human agents can be influenced by their neighbors whether it be human, bot, or algorithmic entities. The algorithm prioritizes engagement when recommending topics, regardless of whether the activity is driven by bots or humans, and does not consider the credibility of the information.

## 2.9 Data Collection

We collect data about which topics humans are interacting with as well as which topic is the algorithm currently pushing. This is visually depicted by a network graph to see which topics agents are interacting with. Additionally, there is a line graph which depicts the numerical number of what agents are interacting with which topics. A topic that is mentioned at a greater rate than others is called “trending topic” and twitter will promote this topic to more users by putting them in the trending list (Annamoradnejad and Habibi, 2019). We have included text to showcase which topic is currently being recommended to agents. This shows how coordinated bot activity can manipulate a topic’s metrics and how algorithm recommendation can amplify a topic.

# §3. Preliminary Observations & Results

## 3.1 Before the Simulation

Our simulation consists of human agents represented by squares and bot agents represented by circles. Additionally, there are six topics to choose from that are differentiated by color (topic1, topic 2, topic3, topic 4, topic 5, topic 6).

Figure 5 shows before the start of the simulation, human agents choose a topic to engage with at random. It is also important to note that at this stage of the simulation, the algorithm has not chosen any topic to push out yet. As the simulation starts, decision bots will coordinate with follower bots to start inflating topic 1\. The main algorithm will then start to recommend the most engaged topic to agents that are in the media ecosystem. While the second algorithm will start to recommend  a chosen  topic at random.

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_5.jpg)

Figure 5\. Simulation before start.

## 3.2 Human Domination

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_6.jpg)

Figure 6\. Simulation of human domination.

In Figure 6, bot agents were pushing to inflate topic 1 while human agents started with a random topic. When the simulation starts, bot agents tried to push out as much engagement as possible to have the algorithm start recommending topic 1 to users. In this instance, the bots failed to manipulate topic 1 to trend. Instead what happened is the human agents had enough influence with one another, that human agents were able to overcome bots influence. In this state of the model, this trail would be classified as narratives being organically grown (human dominated)

We have noticed that this situation appears under a specific set of parameter conditions. It primarily occurs when the bot on human influence is lower in relation to human on human influence. Additionally, the influence of both algorithms are non-existent. Under these conditions, human agents rely more on peer to peer influence rather than algorithmic and bot influence recommendations for topic engagement. As a result, humans are engaging with each other with minimal to non-existent manipulation.

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_7.png)

Figure 7\. Line graph of human domination.

In figure 7, it shows the line graph of our model in a human dominated state. It shows the initial topic that the bots tried to inflate (which is topic 1). Topic 1 had an initial spike of engagement, but it quickly faded out after a couple steps of the simulation. It was then overtaken by human driven topics like topic 5 (pink line) or topic 6 (green line). These topics (5 and 6\) have gained the most amount of engagement without the need for algorithmic interference. This suggests that the absence of algorithms and limited bot influence can make the platform be more authentic, where organic narrative can have more dominance on the platform. Platforms with these types of operating models would be beneficial for human users, this would be attributed to increased user perception of platform information confidence.

## 3.3 Bot Domination

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_8.jpg)

Figure 8\. Simulation of bot domination.

In figure 8, we can see that bots are pushing topic 2 currently and most humans are engaging with topic 2\. Initially the bots were pushing topic 1 and most humans were engaged with said topic, but as time goes on, humans have gained tolerance towards topic 1\. This prompts the bots to try and inflate another topic. The bots then try to push topic 2 towards other agents as a response to this new found tolerance to topic 1\. The bots influence their neighbors quickly which in turn inflates the metrics for engagement for topic 2\. As a response to this new found engagement, the main algorithm picks up topic 2 and pushes it to humans globally throughout the model. In this specific example we end up seeing a feedback loop between both actions, and algorithmic and human responses. Bots were able to trick the algorithm into promoting a topic which in turn prompted more human users to engage with the topic, and resulted with the algorithm being more likely to promote the topic. 

This result is tied to the parameter settings. The bot on human influence is larger than human on human influence, and the main algorithm parameter was set to a high value which allows for the pushing of topics to humans. This scenario is reflective of real world use cases of social media platforms, as most platforms have some form of algorithm serving content to users which are based on total engagement with a topic. To summarize, this trial run of our simulation shows how algorithmic recommendations can be manipulated by bot coordination.

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_9.png)

Figure 9\.  Line graph of bot domination.

Figure 9, shows which topics are engaged over time. We can see topic 1 (yellow) which was initially pushed by bots started to trend and the point in time when humans gained tolerance towards topic 1\. As a response, bots changed to engaging with topic 2 (blue). Topic 2 gained momentum from the new found bot engagement, which was picked by the algorithm and recommended to humans globally.  Human driven topics such as  topic 5 (pink) or topic 6 (green) never gained momentum and ended up being phased out of relevance. This suggests that bot coordination and algorithms can artificially inflate a topic even if it was not initially engaged by humans. This mimics real world examples where misinformation can be spread through social media platforms. Unlike human dominated scenarios, in this case the bot influence and algorithm overwhelmed human organic topics.

## 3.4 Primary Driver of Topics

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_10.jpg)

Figure 10\. Simulation of primary driver.

In figure 10, we purposely disabled both of the algorithms and set the bot on human influence and human on human influence parameters equal to one another. We did this to observe what would happen in the system when all influences are locally based with no global factor like the algorithm. What we saw is there was high fluctuation in topic engagement. Multiple topics spiked for a little but were then overtaken by other topics. No topics remained for a long enough time to consistently be the most engaged topic, where the most engagement topic would fluctuate between one another constantly. 

![My Image](DEL4_Figure_11.png)

Figure 11\. Line graph of primary driver.

In figure 11, the line graph shows how none of the topics are able to maintain dominance over one another. Bots and humans are competing with each other, and all topics were unstable. This result is significant because it shows us that without algorithms, bots are unable to manipulate metrics and dominate the ecosystem.

## 3.4 Emergent Behavior

We initially thought that bots would be the primary driver of trend manipulation. However, in the human dominated scenario. We saw that if bots have weaker influences on humans, we get outcomes where organic topics are able to shape the narrative that surrounds the media ecosystem. An explanation for why this happened could be based on the parameter in the simulation. Where it is based on probability of how the neighbor connected agent has the chance of being influenced. 

An emergent behavior we observed is how the algorithm had an impact on each of the trials. We know that algorithms are strong but we did not think they were the biggest amplifiers of media metrics. As we saw in section 3.3, bots on their own were unable to gain momentum to trend a topic without help of the algorithm. Bots take advantage of the algorithm design and manipulate it to fit their own needs.

# §4. Ethical & Societal Reflections

## 4.1 Ethics

Our project did not use any real world data. All agents, topics, behaviors, and influences were created artificially in the code. Meaning there were no privacy or data usage issues in regards to our model. However if the simulation were to be developed more and integrated into real world datasets, then we would have to be careful about privacy and data collection. As our simulation takes in what the human is engaging with, this will violate TCPS 2 ethics in user privacy and data usage. Users are often anonymous online, but collecting information over time can be used to pinpoint oneself and one's account online. This is important, as TCPS 2 indicates that individuals online have a reasonable expectation of privacy and researchers need to be respectful of user privacy. Another issue we will face is in data usage, we will need to make sure if the user has deleted an account, they would no longer be a part of the simulation.

## 4.2 Social Implications

At the macro level, the simulation shows how manipulation can influence platform trends. Bots can inflate a topic and the algorithm will recommend that topic if engagement reaches a certain threshold. This demonstrates a power structure related between bots and the algorithm, which can be abused for ideological control in regards to information and content moderation. This will lead to AI developments playing a big role in spreading misinformation and fake trends as discourse on social media platforms can potentially impact political and economic trends. 

At the micro level, bots push topics to humans individually, this makes humans believe that the topic is more popular than perceived, and is more likely to engage with it. When humans gain tolerance with the topic and move on from it, bots still have the ability to change topics as well.  This back and forth between users and bots ends up creating a cycle of narrative manipulation which results in it being hard to trust the credibility of information on a platform.

At the meso level, we have seen how the algorithm will change the interaction in small communities. In our simulation, there can be some agents that are not connected to the main network or to all of the bots. They are small in number as well, but can still be impacted by  the algorithm. This can change small online communities in the types of topic they were discussing which brings in new discourse into the community. While this is not inherently bad itself, if the information that comes in is not reliable itself, we circle back into the same problems associated at the micro level but at a larger scale.

## 4.3 Real-World Pattern

This model is realistic as observed in X media ecosystem, it simulates the for you tab on X. one important key is the bots ability to coordinate with one another to amplify a topic. Same as in the real world where bot networks often coordinate to boost a topic to make them more popular. Another realistic element is the algorithm recommendation, the algorithm picks up the topic with the most engagement and does not care about the validity information.

## 4.4 Malicious Intent

We have created this simulation for the purpose to show metric manipulation and vulnerabilities in social media platforms. This simulation as a result can be used as a basis for bad actors to learn the vulnerabilities that social media has. This simulation shows how bots coordinate to influence and manipulate users to make narratives trends. Topics that get picked up by the algorithm tend to spiral out of control in terms of user engagement. Where, if in the wrong hands, can be used to spread misinformation which depending on the severity can have political, health, economic, or even social ramifications. This has been observed in real life in X, where social bots had been plagued by bots leading to amplification of misinformation (Rodrigues et al, 2024\)

# §5. Lessons Learned & Future Directions

## 5.1 Challenges

One of the biggest challenges we faced during development was relating our simulation to our phenomena of interest. The initial network model we had for the simulation only consisted of bots and humans. In this version of our model, bots only had a single degree of form (no active or inactive), bots would influence each other and would influence humans as well. It is important to note that at this early point in development, mechanisms such as the algorithm as well as the topics did not exist. Which made the simulation not reflective of our phenomena of interest (metric manipulation) in the platform. 

To solve this issue, we had to rethink how we want to approach our simulation and modify it. This is when we decided to introduce the topic and an algorithm recommendation mechanism, making the agent interaction more related to our phenomena of interest. We had to re-design agent logic and behaviour as a result. As we now had to consider factors such as how bots would promote a topic and how the algorithm chose the topic to recommend.

One unforeseen challenge we faced during the development was attempting to make the network fully interconnected. This feature was ultimately removed as it could lead to unrelated behaviour that would not be reflective of our phenomena of interest when the amount of agents in the simulation increased. This would be attributed to how following everyone is not reflective of how users typically would conduct themselves on X in actual real life scenarios. To be more realistic we opted for a network that is possible to have agents being not connected to others. We justified our decision to use this because in real life not everyone is following each other meaning that some agents can be generated alone. But, they would still get the topic because of the algorithm recommending it to them.

## 5.2 Model Limitations & Areas for Improvement

Our simulation captures the important interaction and dynamic of metric manipulation in X, but in our model some things have been simplified. We have a predefined topic whereas social media platforms would gradually change over time. Additionally, human agents have simplified behavior compared to their real world counterparts. Human agents get influenced by the topic that is being pushed by the algorithm and gain tolerance toward a topic over time. But in our model, we have it set so that when bots change topics they are trying to inflate, this action resets human tolerance parameters. If we were to further reiterate our model, we would need to implement methods to make the behaviour of agents more sophisticated. An example of this would be to allow for human agents to have parameters to “not be interested” towards a topic and as a result of that action, the algorithm will not push off similar topics to the agent. Another aspect we would change would be variability of bot engagement, bots in real life need to meet certain levels of trustworthiness in humans to not be perceived as bots. Going forward we could introduce a trust parameter to bots, and bots that have low trust parameters will have lower chances of humans engaging with them. This idea can be further expanded upon, where bots with low trust factors will gradually improve their credibility and trust parameters as time progresses in the simulation, to be more reflective of real world tactics of human mimicry of bots.

## 5.3 Future Applications:

Our simulation shows metric manipulation and how trends start in X, as well as how humans, bots and algorithms interact with one another on X. These findings have the potential to make platforms better by understanding bots coordination exploiting algorithm recommendation systems. How bad actors can utilise this vulnerability that X has, which can also have the unintended effect of motivating X to improve their algorithm systems. Seeing how bots have the ability to make topics trend, authoritative bodies may need to take a stance on regulations on algorithmic recommending systems. This would be attributed to how these recommendation systems can have the potential to cause societal ramifications.
